 The previous lemma shows that if the eigenspectrum of a matrix is bounded, we can obtain a Bernstein bound on the error incurred by sampling the trace. Furthermore, the convergence of the series 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:martin"

\end_inset

 is also determined by the extremal eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

. If we truncate the series (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:martin"

\end_inset

), we can bound the truncation error using the extremal eigenvalues. We formalize this intuition in the following theorem, which is adapted from the main theorem in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "Barry1999"

\end_inset

. While that main theorem in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "Barry1999"

\end_inset

 only considered a confidence interval based on the covariance properties of Gaussian distribution, we generalize this result to a more general Bernstein bound. 
